  => "all three live in axis-E (meta-tag) and axis-G (body-field) NAMESPACES — NO leading-char added to arrow LL(1) set"
  => "ORTHOGONALITY vs axis-J: axis-J = REPLACEMENT (row Y supersedes row X; X gets [DEPRECATED] + Y carries superseded_by = X). axis-L2 = REFINEMENT (row Y amends row X; both stay live; X gets [10*AMENDED-BY] + Y carries amends = X). The two axes handle DIFFERENT lifecycle transitions — supersession is destructive (X dies), amendment is constructive (X stays, Y refines)"
  => "ORTHOGONALITY vs axis-K: axis-K = WHEN was the row born. axis-L2 = WHAT MUTATION did it accumulate after birth. axis-K's superseded_at handled death-event timing; axis-L2 introduces amended_at body-field for amendment-event timing — same date-typed parser, different lifecycle role"
  => "FOREIGN CITE-AND-MOVE-ON: append-only event sourcing (Fowler 2005); RFC 7396 JSON merge patch (refinement without replacement); git revision blame (refinement-tracking via VCS); legal amendment-loop (constitution 27 amendments append-only, no retraction) — these are NAMING-PRECEDENT only; the SEMANTICS is atlas.n6's own row-evolution"
  => "intrinsic justification (NOT foreign): atlas.n6 ALREADY uses @M N6HIST-META-AMEND-3PASS (line 27418) to formalise a 3-pass amendment loop; uses 'append-only, no retraction' invariant 18+3 times — axis-L2 EXTRACTS that idiom from prose-buried form into structured body-field form, with the no-retraction invariance preserved as a TYPE-LEVEL constraint (amends = X means X stays live; amends is NOT a synonym for superseded_by)"
  => "axis-K § B7 closure: axis-K § B7 explicitly stated 'Future axes addressing MUTATION (mid-life edits, refinements) are not in scope here — that would be axis-L territory.' axis-L2 is the EXECUTED closure of that deferred slot"

